cs.CG, cs.DS, cs.DM, cs.GT, cs.SI. 

This paper deals with a problem in computational geometry involving points in the plane, which suggests that it belongs to cs.CG (Computational Geometry) category. The use of approximation algorithms and optimization techniques suggests that it could also belong to cs.DS (Data Structures and Algorithms) and cs.SI (Social and Information Networks) categories. The mention of a PTAS for $k=2$ suggests that the paper could also belong to cs.DM (Discrete Mathematics) category. Finally, the use of approximation ratios and Steiner ratio suggests that the paper could also belong to cs.GT (Computer Science and Game Theory) category.
